Recommendations
We recommended, and Management agreed to:
Provide funds for the repair and maintenance of these evacuation centers to ensure that they are readily available in the event of an unexpected disaster;
Conduct urgent repairs to restore the buildings' structural integrity at Barangay Lawigan. Reinforce or rebuild damaged areas to provide a secure environment. Fix the electrical issues so that electricity is available should there be a need for evacuation;
Repair or replace the damaged roofing of comfort rooms at Barangay La Union. Reinstall missing doors to restore privacy and dignity for users; and
Repair or replace the damaged cubicle and floor tiles of the comfort rooms to ensure usability at Barangay Dansalan and restore the water supply for drinking, sanitation and hygiene.

We recommended, and Management agreed to:

1.	 Provide remarks as “Found at Station” and inclusion of non-existing” or “missing” PPEs in the RPCPPE;

2.	Keep record of the alternative activities/procedures undertaken and the reasons for the deviation from the PIP.

3.	Identify the cause for any variance between RPCPPE and accounting records;

4.	Complete the prescribed procedures under COA Circular 2020-06 with regard to items found at station and non-missing PPEs;

5.	Prepare the IIRUP for identified unserviceable items;

6.	Direct Property unit to issue demand letters to those accountable officers for missing PPEs established during the physical count, and cause the conduct of an investigation to determine the responsible persons for the loss, among others; and

7.	Direct the Property and Accounting Units to undertake collaborative reconciliation procedures to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in their corresponding records which includes among others, the maintenance of their respective PC in appropriate forms.

Furthermore, with regard to the identified unrecorded donated PPEs, we recommended and the LCE agreed to:

8.	Direct the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to secure copies of documents and other pertinent records of the donated assets to support the recording in the books of account of the Municipal Accountant;

9.	Direct the GSO to provide property stickers and PC for monitoring of custody and accountability; and

10.	Create appraisal committee for the valuation of the assets in case documents for its measurement are not successfully obtained from the donor LGU especially those assets with Certificate of Registration issued by the Land Transportation Office.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to direct the: 

11.	Municipal Accountant to prepare the Local Road Network Ledger Card (LRNLC), keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network; and prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component at the end of the year;

12.	GSO to maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map, keep a complete LRNPC for all roads and its components, at the end of the accounting period, render a Report of Local Road Network (RLRN) of the LGU concerned;

13.	Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects; and

14.	The Inventory Committee to prepare the RPCRNS of the LGU.

1.	The municipality’s GFPS conduct gender mainstreaming through gender audit and gender analysis of its policies, programs, services and the current situation of the municipality in terms of GAD compliance; 

2.	To equip the GFPS with the in-depth knowledge and capacity on GAD, it also recommended that they shall undergo trainings and seminars such as those relating to gender-responsive planning and budgeting, gender analysis, gender audit and the use of various GAD tools for the LGU’s GAD implementation of PPAs; and

Revisit and strictly comply with the provisions of RA No. 9710 and other provisions of law.

We recommend that the Municipal Government enhance its compliance with policies and procedures on Local Roads Asset Management System by:
Requiring the submission of the report of the Local Road Network by the GSO/Municipal Treasurer in order to implement and monitor the recognition of the account Local Road Network in the books of accounts;

Improving the maintenance of subsidiary ledger for the Road and it components;

Making proper disclosure in the Financial Statement of Road Network System;

Exercising proper reconciliation between Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network and Local Road Network Ledger Card and make the necessary adjustment;

Providing cost to specific Road Network in order to have proper valuation and completeness of the Road Network Account.

We recommended that the municipality’s GFPS shall conduct gender mainstreaming through gender audit and gender analysis of its policies, programs, services and the current situation of the municipality in terms of GAD compliance;
To equip the GFPS with the in-depth knowledge and capacity on GAD, it also recommended that they shall undergo trainings and seminars such as those relating to gender-responsive planning and budgeting, gender analysis, gender audit and the use of various GAD tools for the LGU’s GAD implementation of PPAs; and
Revisit and strictly comply with the provisions of RA No. 9710 and other provisions of law.

We recommend that the Municipality enhance its compliance with policies and procedures in:

Completing the actual physical count and the RPCPPE and reconcile the established differences to have accurate Fixed Asset records and reports for the Municipality for which it is held accountable and provide adequate disclosures to guide the users of information;

Maintaining proper Fixed Asset records for all Municipality’s fixed assets; 

Assigning Fixed Asset to end user or the least the head of office having custody of the assets to facilitate easy monitoring for inventory purposes and ensure that the same are being kept and safeguarded by responsible personnel 

Updating information in the Fixed Asset records;

Coordinating with different personnel/offices of the Municipality in order to gather information as to the amount of acquisition cost and the date of acquisition to be able to recognized depreciation expense.

If no information is available, since in the actual physical count of these assets they are classified as serviceable, proper appraisal on the remaining useful life of the asset should be done and the corresponding depreciation expense shall be computed based on the  book – value as presented in the financial statements.

Disposing unserviceable properties.

